5
00:00:15.000 --> 00:00:21.000
Yes, I do enjoy cooking. I think it's quite relaxing, especially after a busy day.

6
00:00:21.000 --> 00:00:23.000
How about you Baka?

7
00:00:23.000 --> 00:00:29.000
I enjoy cooking when I'm feeding other people, but usually after a busy day work I don't enjoy cooking for myself.

8
00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:41.000
Well, we're talking about cooking today, and most of us can at least boil an egg, but not everyone could make it as a professional chef in a world famous restaurant.

9
00:00:41.000 --> 00:00:54.000
Hmm, being a top chef requires passion, dedication and hard work. Many chefs work 15 hours a day, six days a week, and busy kitchens cooking expensive food are very stressful places to work.

10
00:00:54.000 --> 00:01:06.000
So why do they do it? In this episode we'll hear from one South African chef who started her own award-winning restaurant in the country known as the home of fine dining, France.

11
00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:17.000
As usual we'll be learning some useful new words and phrases, and remember you'll find all this episodes vocabulary along with the transcript on our website, BBCLearningEnglish.com

12
00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:27.000
But first I have a question for you know, the top price for any professional chef are Michelin stars, awards given to restaurants offering outstanding cooking.

13
00:01:27.000 --> 00:01:34.000
But who is the winner of the most Michelin stars ever? Is it a Italian chef and Ricobartelini?

14
00:01:34.000 --> 00:01:40.000
B French chef, Joel Rubasson, or C, British chef Gordon Ramsay?

15
00:01:40.000 --> 00:01:48.000
I'm going to say A, the Italian chef and Ricobartelini, because I went to Italy recently, and the food was amazing.

16
00:01:48.000 --> 00:01:52.000
Hmm, okay, we'll find out the answer later in this episode.

17
00:01:52.000 --> 00:02:02.000
Born in South Africa, chef Jean-Tel.tinal started her culinary career at a three Michelin star restaurant in the exclusive Malfa area of London.

18
00:02:02.000 --> 00:02:10.000
Here, she tells Ruth Alexander, presenter of BBC World Service program The Food Chain, how it all got started.

19
00:02:10.000 --> 00:02:21.000
What happened as I had graduated from the Prudith College of Food and Wine, and decided to send my CV to all the three Michelin star restaurants that I could find at that moment in the Michelin Guide.

20
00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:23.000
So you aim Thai from the off.

21
00:02:23.000 --> 00:02:31.000
I aim Thai, the only thing that they could say was no, and what would I lose? I received a call from chef Paul Rhodes to say,

22
00:02:31.000 --> 00:02:36.000
when can you start? Wow! And this sort of just catapulted my career.

23
00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:40.000
Jean-Tel's and her CV to the world's top restaurants.

24
00:02:40.000 --> 00:02:49.000
CV is short for curriculum for tea, a document listing someone's education, qualifications, and work experience, which they write when looking for a job.

25
00:02:49.000 --> 00:02:52.000
In American English, it's called a resume.

26
00:02:52.000 --> 00:02:59.000
Jean-Tel applied to only Michelin star-winning restaurants. She aimed high, meaning she was ambitious.

27
00:02:59.000 --> 00:03:09.000
Jean-Tel says, the worst they could do is say no. A phrase which means you shouldn't be afraid of trying to do something because the worst outcome is being rejected.

28
00:03:09.000 --> 00:03:12.000
Luckily for Jean-Tel, the answer was yes.

29
00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:18.000
And learning her trade in a top London restaurant catapulted, meaning accelerated her career.

30
00:03:18.000 --> 00:03:26.000
At the age of 26, Jean-Tel left London and returned home to open her own restaurant, Mosaic, near Pretzoria in South Africa.

31
00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:34.000
She'd been inspired by botanical cuisine, the use of edible flowers and herbs to decorate and flavor food.

32
00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:39.000
Here, Jean-Tel tells more to BBC World Service Program for Food Chain.

33
00:03:39.000 --> 00:03:47.000
When I opened Mosaic in South Africa, I knew I wanted something entirely different and something which diners had not seen.

34
00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:51.000
I wanted to have my own signature and to stand out.

35
00:03:51.000 --> 00:03:57.000
And I think especially for botanical cuisine in South Africa, it was very much unknown.

36
00:03:57.000 --> 00:04:07.000
Jean-Tel developed her own signature. A signature item is something that is typical of or strongly associated with a particular person or place.

37
00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:11.000
For example, whiskey is Scotland's signature drink.

38
00:04:11.000 --> 00:04:15.000
Jean-Tel's signature is cooking botanical food.

39
00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:24.000
Jean-Tel's mosaic restaurant is currently at the Shattot detenia in northern France, where it's listed among the top 200 restaurants in the world.

40
00:04:24.000 --> 00:04:30.000
And in 2017, she won the title Best Female Chef in the World.

41
00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:36.000
These achievements have helped Jean-Tel stand out to be more noticeable and better than other chefs.

42
00:04:36.000 --> 00:04:44.000
Jean-Tel is still waiting, but surely it's only a matter of time until she wins those coveted Michelin stars.

43
00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:47.000
Speaking of which, what was the answer to your question, Becca?

44
00:04:47.000 --> 00:04:53.000
Oh yes, I asked you earlier, who is the winner of the most Michelin stars ever?

45
00:04:53.000 --> 00:04:57.000
I said that it was the Italian chef and Riko Bartelini.

46
00:04:57.000 --> 00:05:00.000
But unfortunately, it was incorrect.

47
00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:01.000
Ah, no.

48
00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:10.000
The right answer is B. Joelle Rubasson, our French chef with 31 stars, the most decorated chef in history.

49
00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:19.000
OK, let's recap the vocabulary we've learned, starting with curriculum Vite, CV, or resume in American English.

50
00:05:19.000 --> 00:05:26.000
A document outlining someone's education, qualifications, and work experience, which they prepare when looking for a job.

51
00:05:26.000 --> 00:05:31.000
To aim high means to be ambitious and set high goals.

52
00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:34.000
The phrase, the worst they can do is say no.

53
00:05:34.000 --> 00:05:38.000
Means, don't be afraid of trying to do something for the fear of rejection.

54
00:05:38.000 --> 00:05:42.000
If something is catapulted, it suddenly accelerated or launched forward.

55
00:05:42.000 --> 00:05:47.000
A signature item is something that a person or place is known for.

56
00:05:47.000 --> 00:05:53.000
And finally, to stand out means to be more noticeable or better than other similar things.

57
00:05:53.000 --> 00:05:55.000
Once again, our six minutes are up.

